# MOCT 7 | Cursor AI Rules

This is a live VJ terminal visual engine for a techno event (MOCT 7, Hayfilm Studio, Yerevan 2026).
The user edits visuals.py in real time during performances. Changes hot-reload in ~1 second via os.execv.

## Project layout
- visuals.py     — MAIN FILE. Engine class, 17 visual modes. Edit for visual changes.
- controller.py  — Curses TUI. Edit for controller UI/key changes.
- config.json    — Startup defaults.
- control.json   — Live IPC (controller → visuals, auto-generated).
- status.json    — Live IPC (visuals → controller, auto-generated).
- AI_CONTEXT.md  — Full architecture reference.

## Code rules

- Output: always build list[str] and emit one sys.stdout.write(''.join(out)) per frame for full-grid modes.
  Never write per-cell in a hot loop.
- Colors: use C['red'], C['green'] etc. Always append RESET after colored text.
- Palette: always use self.pal['p'], self.pal['s'], self.pal['a'] — never hardcode colors.
- Drawable area: H = self.h - 1. Bottom row (self.h - 1) is status bar — never draw there.
- Clip text: always text[:self.w - x] before writing.
- Sparse modes (CUBE, SCANNER, STORM, PARTICLES, SHOCKWAVE): use self._put(x, y, ch, col).
- Full-grid modes (TUNNEL, PLASMA, VORTEX, NOISE, WAVE, PULSE): use list-join output.
- No print(), no os.system('clear'), no curses in visuals.py.
- No external dependencies beyond Python stdlib.
- Keep particles capped: self.particles = alive[-700:]
- Keep rings capped: self.rings = alive[-14:]

## Adding a new mode
1. Add def _mymode(self) to Engine
2. Append to self.mode_fns and self.mode_labels in __init__
3. Append name to MODES in controller.py

## Aesthetic
Industrial/techno. Bold ANSI colors. Math-driven animation (sin/cos). BPM-aware where possible.
Characters from self.syms: ['█','▓','▒','░','▚','◈','7','M','O','C','T'].

## Hot reload
The engine watches its own mtime every 20 frames and calls os.execv to restart in-place.
Save visuals.py → user sees the change in ~1 second. No manual restart needed.
